pull_request.body:
This PR implements the first version of the SpaceTraders UI application following the workplan specifications in `WORKPLAN.md` and `ShipAutomation.md`. The implementation successfully completes **Milestone M1** with a fully functional React-based dashboard.

## Key Features Implemented

### 🚀 Complete SpaceTraders API Integration
- Full API client with proper rate limiting (max 2 requests/second as required)
- Support for both Account Tokens (agent registration) and Agent Tokens (operations)
- Error handling with user-friendly messages
- Bearer token authentication following SpaceTraders v2.3.0 specification

### 📱 Mobile-Accessible React UI
- Responsive design that works on both desktop and mobile devices
- Modern React with TypeScript and Vite build system
- Component-based architecture ready for React Native expansion
- Cross-platform storage abstraction using localStorage (ready for AsyncStorage)

### 🎯 Core Dashboard Functionality
- **Agent Information Display**: Shows credits, headquarters, faction, and ship count
- **Fleet Management**: Visual overview of all ships with real-time status indicators
- **Ship Operations**: Basic actions including dock, orbit, and refuel with proper API calls
- **Token Management**: Secure storage and management of authentication tokens

### 🛠 Technical Architecture
```
src/
├── components/          # Reusable UI components (AgentInfo, ShipCard, TokenSetup)
├── context/            # React context for token state management
├── screens/            # Main application screens (Dashboard)
├── services/           # API client with rate limiting and error handling
├── types/              # TypeScript definitions for SpaceTraders API
└── utils/              # Storage, formatting, and utility functions
```

## Screenshots
The application includes:
1. **Token Setup Screen**: Clean interface for entering SpaceTraders agent tokens
2. **Main Dashboard**: Shows agent stats and fleet overview with ship action buttons
3. **Error Handling**: Graceful display of API errors and loading states

## Implementation Notes

- **Rate Limiting**: Implements proper 2 req/second limit to respect SpaceTraders API requirements
- **Security**: Tokens stored securely with proper redaction in logs
- **Error Resilience**: Comprehensive error handling with user feedback
- **Future-Ready**: Architecture supports upcoming milestones (M2-M7) and React Native integration

This establishes the foundation for all remaining features including contracts management, navigation, mining operations, market integration, and eventually the ship automation system described in `ShipAutomation.md`.

The app successfully demonstrates core functionality with real SpaceTraders API integration and provides a solid base for mobile APK generation as requested.

comment.body:
## BURDEN
> A weapon’s burden notes how many hands it takes to wield it. Weapons are either one-handed or two-handed. When you take a weapon, you’ll also fill up a number of hands equal to its burden on your character sheet. If your character can’t bear the burden of a weapon because their hands are already full, you can’t equip it.  
> 
> You’re welcome to create a character with any number of hands or have your character wield a weapon using something other than their hands. However, when tracking burden, each character mechanically has two appendages capable of wielding weapons.

While "balancing" is not the focus of the system, `Burden` is clearly a balancing feature of it. I get that logically the hands don't matched, but I think dropping `Torch` and *using* the already `Equiped` (*prepared*/*readied*?) `Weapons` should not be at the cost of `Switching Weapons`. Note that while the section includes `Equipment`, the subsection introducing the resource cost is only `Switching Weapong` (pg. 112).

issue.title: "Huawei Batteries Maximum Discharging Power (W)" - Exceeding Battery's capabilities
issue.body: I'm currently testing the HSEM, which seems to be very promising (as today I'm controlling my battery's behavior via complex automations, which are not always as reliable as needed). However, I stumbled across the following bug/problem: According to the log files the HSEM integration seems to be setting the maximum discharge power of the battery to **5000 W**. The only problem is, that not all batteries are capable of charging/discharging that much power. The `Huawei Solar` integration is paying respect to that by limiting the respective number sensor's range accordingly (based on the maximum power capabilities according to the respective modbus register). e.g.: The Luna2000 with 5 kWh capacity can only charge/discharge a power of **2500 W**. That led to the problem, that the integration couldn't update the maximum discharge sensor... ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/helpers/entity_platform.py", line 676, in _async_add_entities await self._async_add_entity( entity, False, entity_registry, config_subentry_id ) File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/helpers/entity_platform.py", line 1002, in _async_add_entity await entity.add_to_platform_finish() File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/helpers/entity.py", line 1380, in add_to_platform_finish await self.async_added_to_hass() File "/config/custom_components/hsem/custom_sensors/working_mode_sensor.py", line 2506, in async_added_to_hass await self._async_handle_update(None) File "/config/custom_components/hsem/custom_sensors/working_mode_sensor.py", line 641, in _async_handle_update await self._async_set_working_mode() File "/config/custom_components/hsem/custom_sensors/working_mode_sensor.py", line 1042, in _async_set_working_mode await async_set_number_value( ...<3 lines>... ) File "/config/custom_components/hsem/utils/misc.py", line 222, in async_set_number_value await self.hass.services.async_call( ...<7 lines>... ) File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/core.py", line 2835, in async_call response_data = await coro ^^^^^^^^^^ File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/core.py", line 2878, in _execute_service return await target(service_call) ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/helpers/service.py", line 850, in entity_service_call single_response = await _handle_entity_call( ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ hass, entity, func, data, call.context ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ ) ^ File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/helpers/service.py", line 922, in _handle_entity_call result = await task ^^^^^^^^^^ File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/components/number/__init__.py", line 106, in async_set_value raise ServiceValidationError( ...<8 lines>... ) homeassistant.exceptions.ServiceValidationError: Value 5000.0 for number.battery_maximale_entladeleistung is outside valid range 0.0 - 2500 ``` ...and subsequently also couldn't initialize the working mode sensor. This is being caused by the 5000 W to be hardcoded: https://github.com/woopstar/hsem/blob/04495d16404de2577e6c473e669cfe738e8c54d9/custom_components/hsem/custom_sensors/working_mode_sensor.py#L1036-L1046 I assume that the hardcoded value of **5000 W** will also be used for charging / discharging time calculations, right? It might be a better approach to read the maximum charge and discharge values (e.g. by checking the sensor attributes). Let me know, in case additional logs/tests would be of any help. Cheers Mat

issue.title: Handle release stats for multi-per-day podcasts
issue.body: ### Description Fixes a bug where stats were rendering incorrectly for podcasts with multiple-per-day releases. The prediction code is already pretty good for podcasts released daily or less frequently so I prioritized leaving that alone as much as possible. With multiple for day, the next release will very commonly be "any time now" since we before this we standardized on a granularity of days. Any predictions for when inside the day podcasts will release may require some rethinking. This should correctly handle cases where a podcast releases multiple episodes some days and none other days (a test case was added for this) Prior to this, running the real world data test `testRealWorld()` gave the following results: ``` Podcasts tested: 482 Found schedule: 80.70539419087137 Off by less than 3 hours: 55.3941908713693 Correct day when schedule found: 71.72236503856041 Correct day: 59.75103734439834 Off by less than 2 days: 72.19917012448133 ``` After the changes, the results are: ``` Podcasts tested: 482 Found schedule: 82.57261410788382 Off by less than 3 hours: 58.09128630705394 Correct day when schedule found: 74.37185929648241 Correct day: 62.448132780082986 Off by less than 2 days: 73.02904564315352 ``` Closes: #7679 ### Checklist - [x] I have read the contribution guidelines: https://github.com/AntennaPod/AntennaPod/blob/develop/CONTRIBUTING.md#submit-a-pull-request - [x] I have performed a self-review of my code - [x] I have run the automated code checks using `./gradlew checkstyle spotbugsPlayDebug spotbugsDebug :app:lintPlayDebug` - [x] My code follows the style guidelines of the AntennaPod project: https://github.com/AntennaPod/AntennaPod/wiki/Code-style - [x] I have mentioned the corresponding issue and the relevant keyword (e.g., "Closes: #xy") in the description (see https://docs.github.com/en/issues/tracking-your-work-with-issues/linking-a-pull-request-to-an-issue) - [x] If it is a core feature, I have added automated tests
